      <bioghist id="aspace_0ff5d49c8b70f97934a36bdd6a247afa">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Daniel Pinello is a writer, lawyer, and professor of political science at John Jay College of Criminal Justice. In October 1971, he penned an essay entitled "The Homosexual at Williams: Coming Out," which made the front page of the student newspaper at Williams College. This essay, along with his subsequent thesis on the lead-up and experiences following the public outing, garnered a Henry Rutgers Conger Memorial Literary Prize in 1972 for best piece of student journalism in an undergraduate publication. Since publication of the original essay, Pinello has written several books on same-sex rights including "America's War on Same-Sex Couples and Their Families - And How the Courts Rescued Them" in 2017. The working title of Pinello's autobiography is <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Equal: A Memoir of Gay Rights</part>
            </title>.</p>
         <p>Professor Frederick Rudolph of the College's History Department supervised Pinello's honors thesis, which explored Pinello's experiences coming out in 1971. Rudolph and Pinello corresponded for several years afterwards. Pinello includes a chapter in his autobiography about those conversations.</p>
         <p>Rudolph died in 2013 at the age of 93.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_8366eca4b6c964023fae0454c3ae8e4b">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Daniel Pinello papers. General Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_486816fec68eb4bfc5da4802f6bbb943">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection contains thirty letters to Daniel Pinello from his former honors thesis advisor, Williams College professor Frederick Rudolph.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_8fd9ac8ab9e87a62fdc7bd1ae85548cc">
